  "body": "I configured haproxy for node failover. I am using <code>http-check expect rstring</code> and haproxy does not use keep-alive with <code>http-check</code>. This is sniff by <code>ngrep</code>:\n\n```\n#############\nT 127.0.0.1:53038 -> 127.0.0.1:8545 [AP]\n  POST / HTTP/1.1..Host: 127.0.0.1:8545..Accept: */*..Content-Type: application/json..Content-Length: 59....{\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"method\":\"eth_getWork\",\"params\":[],\n  \"id\":1}..Connection: close....\n##\nT 127.0.0.1:8545 -> 127.0.0.1:53038 [AP]\n  HTTP/1.1 200 OK..Content-Type: application/json..Date: Wed, 26 Aug 2015 15:17:14 GMT..Content-Length: 243....{\"id\":1,\"jsonrpc\":\"2.0\",\"result\":[\"0x15fd6d469043\n  a96604aae118c2663d53e5aa338c755842955f00ca3207a04f15\",\"0xb903bd7696740696b2b18bd1096a2873bb8ad0c2e7f25b00a0431014edb3f539\",\"0x000000000031e01bf11e5f80a7cc28b8\n  2b89044287811128934e395fe0f5c402\"]}.\n##\nT 127.0.0.1:8545 -> 127.0.0.1:53038 [AP]\n  HTTP/1.1 400 Bad Request....\n########\n```\n\nYou can see that there is 1 request and 2 different responses from geth. I am sure that geth should not  return 400 error.\n",
